Group 13: Sanjit Saji, Shreya Rathi & Aryan Shah

Executive Summary: Predicting IPL Match Outcomes

Our analysis for this project explores how we can estimate the chance of winning as the match progresses in the Indian Premier League (IPL). We use detailed ball-by-ball data from every mens IPL match that is available through the Cricsheet database. Our group aims to quantify how factors like remaining runs, wickets in hand, and scoring rate influence the likelihood of a successful chase. The goal is to build an interpretable and data-driven model that can estimate, at any point in the second innings, what is the probability that the current batting team will win.

Approach and Data

The data consists of every ball delivery from IPL matches from 2008 to 2025. We trained the model on data from 2008-2024, focusing on second-innings situations (where teams chase a set target). The data contained over a million deliveries, which were then cleaned to remove incomplete records and end-of-innings edge cases such as all out or target already reached. For each ball, contextual features were engineered to capture the game state: - Runs required and balls remaining (pressure indicators) - Wickets in hand (resources left) - Current vs.required run rate (momentum balance) - Indicators for powerplay and death overs (phase of innings)

The resulting dataset allowed the modeling of win probability at every delivery rather than at match level, giving a dynamic view of team performance and decision-making.

Modeling Framework

Three predictive models were built and compared: 1. Logistic Regression a simple, interpretable model estimating how each factor shifts the odds of winning. 2. Random Forest an ensemble approach capturing complex, nonlinear interactions. 3. XGBoost with Cricket-Specific Monotonic Constraints a modern gradient-boosting model guided by domain knowledge (e.g., needing more runs should never increase win probability). All models were trained on data from 20082024 and tested on 2025 matches to assess how well they generalize.

Key Findings

  • Runs required, required run rate, and wickets in hand emerged as the strongest predictors of success.
  • Win probability drops sharply when the required run rate exceeds 10 runs per over or when fewer than 4 wickets remain.
  • The Random Forest and XGBoost models both outperformed Logistic Regression in capturing late-game momentum shifts, though the simpler logistic model remained valuable for interpretability.
  • Model calibration showed predicted win probabilities closely matched actual outcomes, indicating reliable estimates across situations.

Applications

The resulting framework can provide real-time insights for coaches, broadcasters, and analysts such as visual win probability graphs after every ball or objective evaluation of tactical choices (e.g., when to accelerate scoring or retain key batters). Teams can also use the feature importances to refine strategy, such as understanding the critical balance between preserving wickets and maintaining scoring pressure.

Limitations and Next Steps

While models were trained on a large dataset, they do not yet incorporate contextual factors like pitch conditions, bowler quality, or player fatigue. Future extensions could include richer tracking or player-level data and adaptation for other leagues or womens cricket.

Technical Report: Predicting IPL Match Outcomes

1. Objective

The goal of this analysis is to build data-driven models that estimate the win probability of an IPL team during a match, based on dynamic match variables like required runs, wickets in hand, and overs remaining. The dataset spans IPL seasons 20082025, offering 124,666 training observations and 8,092 test samples from 72 matches in the 2025 season.

2. Data Preparation

The data was imported via the cricketdata package (fetch_cricsheet("bbb", "male", "ipl")), cleaned to remove incomplete records, and transformed to compute ball-level features.

The raw data includes both innings of each match as well as abandoned or incomplete games. Since the goal is to model win probability, the analysis focuses exclusively on the second innings, where the target is known and the outcome (win/loss) is deterministically observable ball by ball.

After cleaning:

  • Training rows: 124,666
  • Test rows: 8,092
  • Target variable: won (binary 0/1 for team victory)

Training/Test Split

  • Training set: Seasons 2008-2024
  • Test set: Season 2025

Choosing variables that are most valuable

Focusing on the Second Innings data only

Restricting the analysis to the second innings provides several modeling advantages:

  • The target score is fixed, allowing clear definition of runs required and win probability.

  • The outcome variable (won) is known at every ball - unlike first innings, where the eventual chase context is unknown.

  • It reflects real-time prediction opportunities during live matches.

In practice, this choice transforms the problem into a dynamic binary classification task, where each ball in the chase is a new observation with updated state variables.

3. Logistic Regression Model

The logistic regression was used as a baseline model, trained to predict the probability of winning (won) from seven continuous and categorical features.

Key insights:

  • Required run rate had a strong negative coefficient (high pressure reduces win chance).
  • Wickets in hand and current run rate had positive effects, confirming the expected cricket intuition.
  • Model convergence warnings occurred due to extreme match states (outcomes nearly deterministic).

Performance summary:

  • Training mean predicted probability: 0.465
  • Test mean: 0.390
  • Indicates mild underconfidence (slight underprediction of win chance).

4. Random Forest Model

To capture nonlinear interactions, a Random Forest classifier was trained using the same features.

Top Predictors (MeanDecreaseGini):

Calibration:

  • RF average predicted = 0.380
  • Miscalibration = 0.095, indicating conservative predictions.

5. XGBoost Model

The final model used gradient boosting with monotonic constraints, ensuring cricket-aware behavior (win probability increases with wickets, decreases with required rate).

Cross-validation log-loss: 0.4383 Best test set calibration: = 0.0724 (smallest among all models). Training time: 7.6 s fastest of the ensemble models.

Handles 2025 data better than others Cricket-aware monotone constraints ensure logical predictions

Interpretation:

  • XGBoost achieved the lowest calibration error, learning a smoother win-probability curve across game contexts.
  • Logistic regression remained interpretable but too rigid for nonlinear dynamics.
  • RF captured complex interactions but was more prone to overconfidence.
  • All models consistently ranked match states similarly ( 0.90 between Logit and RF).

7. Model Validation & Visualization

ROC curves were plotted for all models on 2025 test data:

A separate calibration plot was also generated confirming that XGBoosts predictions align most closely with the 45 reference line (perfect calibration).

The model validation shows that all three models predict match outcomes accurately, but with different strengths:

  • XGBoost provided the best overall performance - highest AUC and most reliable calibration, meaning its predicted win probabilities closely matched actual results.

  • Random Forest captured momentum shifts well but slightly underestimated win chances in tight games.

  • Logistic Regression was interpretable and stable but less responsive to late-innings dynamics.

Overall, XGBoost generalizes best on unseen data, offering accurate, well-calibrated, and cricket-aware win probability estimates that track real match situations effectively.

8. Key Findings and Practical Use

Model Characteristics

  • Training samples: 124,666 balls (20082024)
  • Test samples: 8,092 balls (2025)
  • Features: 7 match-state variables

Practical Applications

  • Real-time win probability tracking for live IPL broadcasts
  • In-game strategy optimization (e.g., wicket conservation, over pacing)
  • Enhanced fan engagement via dynamic win probability graphics

10. Conclusion

All three models effectively predict win probabilities from live match data, with XGBoost emerging as the most accurate and cricket-consistent model. It balances interpretability, computational efficiency, and real-world performance - making it suitable for integration into broadcast dashboards or team analytics systems.
